@raindev

> Why aren't ordinary functions good enough for the same purpose?

https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/0195-associated-items.md#user-content-expressiveness

Out of curiosity, would something like the snippet below work in a recent Rust version? I'm thinking either the most recent stable, or straight up nightly.

````
#![feature(associated_consts)]

pub struct Foo(/* elided */);

impl Foo {
    pub const MY_CONST: &'static str = "hurr durr I'm a sheep";

    // Other defs elided
}
````

I'm able to get away with using this instead of `const fn` for certain types of "constructors" in order to yield a better API. For example:

```
pub struct SomeType<T> {
    // Some fields that are intentionally private...
}

impl<T> SomeType<T> {
    pub const DEFAULT: Self = Self {
        // Initialize fields...
    };
}

// Now we can create new `SomeType<T>` values generic over T without a function call...
let value: SomeType<i32> = SomeType::DEFAULT;

// Better example of what I actually want to allow...
pub static VALUE: SomeType<i32> = SomeType::DEFAULT;
```

The current stable alternative is to make all fields public and to use a macro for initialization.

@withoutboats I think that was because I told @brson the two features are related.
However, after #40008, everything except type parameters in array lengths should work.
We could even stabilize the feature as it is right now, and your usecase would be covered.

@eddyb That's great to hear. I triaged the open issues linked from this thread & I agree that we could stabilize this feature in the short term. Maybe someone else has reason not to, but there's an easy way to hear from them...

@rfcbot fcp merge

@rust-lang/lang I propose we stabilize associated consts. :tada:

On their own they're not that *useful* (because they're primarily *useful* as the input to constexprs, of which array lengths are the only stable example), but they have a more "para-semantic" use as a more precise way to express oneself.

That is, today I might write:

```rust
trait Whatever {
    fn name() -> &'static str;
}
```

But what I really want to write is:

```rust
trait Whatever {
    const NAME: &'static str;
}
```

This is both more ergonomic & it more clearly expresses *user intent* than the associated function form.

There are currently two outstanding shortcomings tracked:

* __Type params in const expressions:__ ( #34344 / #39211 ) A const expression (such as an array length) cannot today depend on an abstract type parameter. That is `for<T: Trait> [_; T::CONST]` is not usable; it returns a clean error. However, `[_; i32::CONST]` _does_ work. In my opinion, stabilization need not be blocked by this. **Proposal: No work needed.**

* __Associated consts and object safety:__ ( #26847) Today, associated consts are considered object safe, but if you attempt to access the associated const of a trait object type (as in `<Trait as Trait>::CONST`) you get an ICE. I think the most conservative thing to do is to make associated consts (like associated functions) non-object safe. **Proposal: make associated consts not object safe; block stabilization on this.**

@withoutboats `T::Assoc` does not determine `T`, so `T` cannot appear *solely* in projections in an `impl` header, i.e. `impl<T: Trait> Foo for T::Assoc` gives an error that `T` is unconstrained.
Also, `T::Assoc` is considered to overlap with *any other type* (as it could be that type), for coherence.

`[U; T::CONST]` should have both of those behaviors, at least initially, and that is backwards-compatible with *any other scheme* (at least those that I know of/can think of right now), as it's the most conservative.

I donno if [this](https://is.gd/gjDbpN) comes under https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/34344 but it throws _error[E0311]: the parameter type `P` may not live long enough_.

If we want to copy a `const` between trait `impl`s, then we need a `'static` bound on either `P` or `Self`, which seems overly restrictive. 
```
pub trait Params: Sized {
    /// Unique version identifier for the protocol
    const PROTOCOL_NAME: u64;
}

pub struct ParamsEtc<P: Params>(P);
impl<P> Params for ParamsEtc<P> where P: Params {
    const PROTOCOL_NAME: u64
     = P::PROTOCOL_NAME;
}
```

**Edit** Appears the bound `PhantomData<P>: 'static` works, which likely provides a work around, but also indicates the original error is really a bug.

> Primarily, I am concerned that the existing impl is "ad hoc" in various ways and that we may discover surprising things that it allows or disallows.

Yes, and I've run into these since turning it on, though they've all been things where the current implementation is too conservative.

For example, this works, but requires a `'static` bound that's definitely unnecessary:

```rust
trait Foo {
    const FOO: u32;
}

trait Bar {
    const BAR: u32;
}

impl<T: Foo + 'static> Bar for T {
    const BAR: u32 = T::FOO;
}
```

This doesn't work, even though it should:

```rust
// This trait works:
trait Foo {
    const FOO: Option<String>;
}

trait Bar {
    const BAR: Option<String>;
}

// This impl doesn't work, conservatively assumes T::FOO may have a destructor
impl<T: Foo + 'static> Bar for T {
    const BAR: Option<String> = T::FOO;
}
```

However, where this does work its strictly more expressive than you might expect from the errors you get for `[T; T::LEN]`, even if its strictly less expressive than it ought to be. It seems jagged and surprising but ultimately implementation bugs & I think that it doesn't have to block stabilization but YMMV.

Just so I don't forget, this doesn't work right now ([playpen](https://play.rust-lang.org/?gist=5a332ddf940e55c4f8a3f9be157857c2&version=nightly&backtrace=1)):
```rust
trait Foo {
    const X: i32 = 0;
}

trait Bar: Foo {
    // error: cannot use an outer type parameter in this context
    const Y: i32 = Self::X;
}
```
IIRC on the branch I started working towards `[T; T::N]` fixes this, I'll extract that into a PR.

It wasn't entirely obvious to me what would happen, so I also just tried using `Foo` rather than `Self`, like so:

```` rust
trait Foo {
    const X: i32 = 0;
}

trait Bar: Foo {
    // error: cannot use an outer type parameter in this context
    const Y: i32 = Foo::X;
}
````

The result in the playpen is the same as if `Self` had been used.

Is there any plan to introduce LEN (or similar attribute) as associated const for the built-in rust-primitives 'arrray' or 'slice'? , for example 

const N : usize = b"my_byte_string"::LEN;

or 

is there any plan to declare std::intrinsics::size_of_val(v)  as const-fn(?) enabling somehing like:
#![feature(core_intrinsics)]
const N: usize = unsafe { std::intrinsics::size_of_val(b"my_byte_string") };

Shouldn't equality bounds be possible with associated consts? The following does not compile today:

```rust
trait Foo {
    const BAR: usize;
}

// error: expected type, found `10`
fn f<T: Foo<BAR = 10>>() { }
```

The original [associated items RFC](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/blob/master/text/0195-associated-items.md#constraining-associated-types) makes it clear that this should be possible. I'm wondering: was this simply forgotten about? Or perhaps there are/were complications with implementing this?

Furthermore, using an associated const as an array size does not appear to work:

```rust
pub trait Can {
    const SIZE: usize;
}

fn f<T: Can>(t: T) {
    // error[E0277]: the trait bound `T: Can` is not satisfied
    let x = [0u8; <T as Can>::SIZE];
}
```

There error message is clearly wrong, so this is either a bug in `rustc` or unimplemented functionality resulting in a bogus error message.

I don't know if this is the same issue that @eddyb mentioned here: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/29646#issuecomment-300929548

```rust
trait Foo { const A: usize; }
fn foo<F: Foo>(f: F) {
    const B: usize = F::A; // ERROR
    let b = F::A; // OK
}
```

@gnzlbg Those are two items nested in eachother, we don't allow "inheriting" type parameters in such a situation and it'd be a significant language change to start doing that.
IOW, what you wrote is more or less equivalent to:
```rust
const __HIDDEN_B: usize = F::A;
fn foo<F: Foo>(f: F) {
    use self::__HIDDEN_B as B;
}
```
(and this is not in any way, shape, or form, specific to `const` or associated `const`)

@vks I cannot reproduce this. `rustdoc a.rs` with the code below does document the constant.

```rust
pub struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    pub const BAR: u32 = 7;
}
```

@SimonSapin I think the problem is: 

```rust
pub struct Foo;

impl Foo {
    /// This doc comment won't be shown anywhere.
    pub const BAR: u32 = 7;
}
```
